# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: batch-cmd
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] A **batch file** is a script file in DOS, OS/2 and Microsoft Windows.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] It consists of a series of commands to be executed by the command-line interpreter, stored in a plain text file.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] A batch file may contain any command the interpreter accepts interactively and use constructs that enable conditional branching and looping within the batch file, such as `IF`, `FOR`, and `GOTO` labels.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The term "batch" is from batch processing, meaning "non-interactive execution", though a batch file might not process a *batch* of multiple data.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Similar to Job Control Language (JCL), DCL and other systems on mainframe and minicomputer systems, batch files were added to ease the work required for certain regular tasks by allowing the user to set up a script to automate them.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] When a batch file is run, the shell program (usually COMMAND.COM or cmd.exe) reads the file and executes its commands, normally line-by-line.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Unix-like operating systems, such as Linux, have a similar, but more flexible, type of file called a shell script.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The filename extension **.bat** is used in DOS and Windows.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Windows NT and OS/2 also added **.cmd**.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Batch files for other environments may have different extensions, e.g., **.btm** in 4DOS, 4OS2 and 4NT related shells.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The detailed handling of batch files has changed significantly between versions.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Some of the detail in this article applies to all batch files, while other details apply only to certain versions.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] In MS-DOS, a batch file can be started from the command-line interface by typing its name, followed by any required parameters and pressing the ↵ Enter key.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] When DOS loads, the file AUTOEXEC.BAT, when present, is automatically executed, so any commands that need to be run to set up the DOS environment may be placed in this file.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Computer users would have the AUTOEXEC.BAT file set up the system date and time, initialize the DOS environment, load any resident programs or device drivers, or initialize network connections and assignments.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Microsoft Windows was introduced in 1985 as a graphical user interface-based (GUI) overlay on text-based operating systems and was designed to run on DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] In order to start it, the `WIN` command was used, which could be added to the end of the AUTOEXEC.BAT file to allow automatic loading of Windows.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] In the earlier versions, one could run a .bat type file from Windows in the MS-DOS Prompt.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Windows 3.1x and earlier, as well as Windows 9x invoked COMMAND.COM to run batch files.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The IBM OS/2 operating system supported DOS-style batch files.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] It also included a version of REXX, a more advanced batch-file scripting language.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] OS/2's batch file interpreter also supports an EXTPROC command.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] This passes the batch file to the program named on the EXTPROC file as a data file.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The named program can be a script file; this is similar to the #! mechanism used by Unix-like operating systems.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Unlike Windows 98 and earlier, the Windows NT family of operating systems does not depend on MS-DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Windows NT introduced an enhanced 32-bit command interpreter (cmd.exe) that could execute scripts with either the .CMD or .BAT extension.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Cmd.exe added additional commands, and implemented existing ones in a slightly different way, so that the same batch file (with different extension) might work differently with cmd.exe and COMMAND.COM.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] In most cases, operation is identical if the few unsupported commands are not used.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Cmd.exe's extensions to COMMAND.COM can be disabled for compatibility.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Microsoft released a version of cmd.exe for Windows 9x and ME called WIN95CMD to allow users of older versions of Windows to use certain cmd.exe-style batch files.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] As of Windows 8, cmd.exe is the normal command interpreter for batch files; the older COMMAND.COM can be run as well in 32-bit versions of Windows able to run 16-bit programs.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] This extension runs with DOS and all versions of Windows, under COMMAND.COM or cmd.exe, despite the different ways the two command interpreters execute batch files.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] family and sent to cmd.exe for interpretation.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] COMMAND.COM does not recognize this file name extension, so cmd.exe scripts are not executed in the wrong Windows environment by mistake.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] variable only upon an error, whereas from within a .cmd file, they would affect errorlevel even when returning without an error.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] It is also used by IBM's OS/2 for batch files.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] These scripts are faster, especially with longer ones, as the script is loaded entirely ready for execution, rather than line-by-line.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] COMMAND.COM and cmd.exe can run a batch file even if its filename is typed without an extension.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] For instance, if `DoThis` is entered, the interpreter tries the following extensions in the order given: `COM`, `.EXE`, `.BAT`, `.CMD`, and seven other extension unrelated to this topic.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The PATHEXT environment variable can change the aforesaid default.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] COMMAND.COM and cmd.exe support special variables (`%0`, `%1` through `%9`) in order to refer to the path and name of the batch job and the first nine calling parameters from within the batch job, see also SHIFT.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Non-existent parameters are replaced by a zero-length string.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] They can be used similar to environment variables, but are not stored in the environment.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Microsoft and IBM refer to these variables as *replacement parameters* or *replaceable parameters*, whereas Digital Research, Novell and Caldera established the term *replacement variables* for them.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] JP Software calls them *batch file parameters*.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] This example batch file displays `Hello World!`, prompts and waits for the user to press a key, and then terminates.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] To execute the file, it must be saved with the filename extension suffix .bat (or .cmd for Windows NT-type operating systems) in plain text format, typically created by using a text editor such as Microsoft Notepad or a word processor working in plain text mode.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The interpreter executes each line in turn, starting with the first.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The `@` symbol at the start of any line prevents the prompt from displaying that command as it is executed.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The command `ECHO OFF` turns off the prompt permanently, or until it is turned on again.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The combined `@ECHO OFF` is often as here the first line of a batch file, preventing any commands from displaying, itself included.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Then the next line is executed and the `ECHO Hello World!` command outputs `Hello World!`.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The next line is executed and the `PAUSE` command displays `Press any key to continue . . .` and pauses the script's execution.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] After a key is pressed, the script terminates, as there are no more commands.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] In Windows, if the script is executed from an already running command prompt window, the window remains open at the prompt as in MS-DOS; otherwise, the window closes on termination.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Variable expansions are substituted textually into the command, and thus variables which contain nothing simply disappear from the syntax, and variables which contain spaces turn into multiple tokens.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The usual way to prevent this problem is to surround variable expansions in quotes so that an empty variable expands into the valid expression `IF ""=="bar"` instead of the invalid `IF ==bar`.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The text that is being compared to the variable must also be enclosed in quotes, because the quotes are not special delimiting syntax; these characters represent themselves.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The delayed !VARIABLE! expansion available in Windows 2000 and later may be used to avoid these syntactical errors.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Another difference in Windows 2000 or higher is that an empty variable (undefined) is not substituted.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] As described in previous examples, previous batch interpreter behaviour would have resulted in an empty string.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Batch interpreters prior to Windows 2000 would have displayed result `MyVar is not defined`.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Unlike Unix/POSIX processes, which receive their command-line arguments already split up by the shell into an array of strings, a Windows process receives the entire command-line as a single string, via the GetCommandLine API function.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] As a result, each Windows application can implement its own parser to split the entire command line into arguments.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Many applications and command-line tools have evolved their own syntax for doing that, and so there is no single convention for quoting or escaping metacharacters on Windows command lines.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Some characters, such as pipe (`|`) characters, have special meaning to the command line.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] However, escaping does not work as expected when inserting the escaped character into an environment variable.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The variable ends up containing a live pipe command when merely echoed.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Until the TIMEOUT command was introduced with Windows Vista, there was no easy way to implement a timed pause, as the PAUSE command halts script activity indefinitely until any key is pressed.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Many workarounds were possible, but generally only worked in some environments: The `CHOICE` command was not available in older DOS versions, `PING` was only available if TCP/IP was installed, and so on.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] No solution was available from Microsoft, but a number of small utility programs, could be installed from other sources.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] A commercial example would be the 1988 Norton Utilities Batch Enhancer (BE) command, where `BE DELAY 18` would wait for 1 second, or the free 94-byte WAIT.COM where `WAIT 5` would wait for 5 seconds, then return control to the script.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Most such programs are 16-bit .COM files, so are incompatible with 64-bit Windows.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Normally, all printed text automatically has the control characters for carriage return (CR) and line feed (LF) appended to the end of each line.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] A trick discovered with Windows 2000 and later is to use the special prompt for input to output text without CR/LF trailing the text.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] However, there is no way to inject this stripped CR/LF prompt output directly into an environment variable.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] It is not possible to have a command prompt that uses a UNC path as the current working directory; e.g.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The command prompt requires the use of drive letters to assign a working directory, which makes running complex batch files stored on a server UNC share more difficult.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] While a batch file can be run from a UNC file path, the working directory default is `C:\Windows\System32\`.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] In Windows 2000 and later, a workaround is to use the **`PUSHD`** and **`POPD`** command with command extensions.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] If not enabled by default, command extensions can be temporarily enabled using the `/E:ON` switch for the command interpreter.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The working directory attribute of this shortcut is ignored.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] This also solves a problem related to User Account Control (UAC) on Windows Vista and newer.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] When an administrator is logged on and UAC is enabled, and they try to run a batch file as administrator from a network drive letter, using the right-click file context menu, the operation will unexpectedly fail.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] This is because the elevated UAC privileged account context does not have network drive letter assignments, and it is not possible to assign drive letters for the elevated context via the Explorer shell or logon scripts.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] However, by creating a shortcut to the batch file using the above `PUSHD` / `POPD` construct, and using the shortcut to run the batch file as administrator, the temporary drive letter will be created and removed in the elevated account context, and the batch file will function correctly.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The following syntax does correctly expand to the path of the current batch script.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] UNC default paths are turned off by default as they used to crash older programs.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The Dword registry value `DisableUNCCheck` at `HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Microsoft\Command Processor` allows the default directory to be UNC.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] `CD` command will refuse to change but placing a UNC path in Default Directory in a shortcut to Cmd or by using the Start command.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Batch files use an OEM character set, as defined by the computer, e.g.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The non-ASCII parts of these are incompatible with the Unicode or Windows character sets otherwise used in Windows so care needs to be taken.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Non-English file names work only if entered through a DOS character set compatible editor.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] File names with characters outside this set do not work in batch files.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] To get a command prompt with Unicode instead of Code page 437 or similar, one can use the `cmd /U` command.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] In such a command prompt, a batch file with Unicode filenames will work.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Also one can use `cmd /U` to directly execute commands with Unicode as character set.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] For example, `cmd /U /C dir > files.txt` creates a file containing a directory listing with correct Windows characters, in the UTF-16LE encoding.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] As with any other programming language, batch files can be used maliciously.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Simple trojans and fork bombs are easily created, and batch files can do a form of DNS poisoning by modifying the hosts file.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] Batch viruses are possible, and can also spread themselves via USB flash drives by using Windows' Autorun capability.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The cmd.exe command processor that interprets both `.bat` and `.cmd` files is supported in all versions of the Windows NT family, Windows CE, and ReactOS.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] The older COMMAND.COM, which only interprets `.bat` files, is available in Windows 9x and 32-bit editions of Windows NT; hence, it is not available in Windows 11, which is strictly 64-bit.
[src:batch-cmd/batch-file] There are other scripting languages available for Windows.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] Older, related operating systems, DOS and Windows 9x, provided COMMAND.COM as the shell. cmd.exe replaced COMMAND.COM in the Windows product line with the introduction of NT.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] Current versions of Windows include PowerShell as an alternative shell that runs side-by-side with cmd.exe.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] The initial version of cmd.exe for Windows NT was developed by Therese Stowell.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] Windows CE 2.11 was the first embedded Windows release to support a console and a Windows CE version of cmd.exe.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] The ReactOS implementation of cmd.exe is derived from FreeCOM, the FreeDOS command line interpreter.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] In Windows, the shell is presented in the desktop via Windows Terminal or on older versions via Windows Console.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] In OS/2 and Windows, the shell supports pipes to allow both sides of a pipeline to run concurrently.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] As a result, it is possible to redirect the standard error stream.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] In contrast, COMMAND.COM uses temporary files, and runs the two sides serially, one after the other.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] Multiple commands can be included in a single line using the command separators `&`, `&&` or `||`.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] With the `&` separator, a subsequent command is executed even if the previous command indicates an error.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] In the following example, each of the three commands is executed, one after the other, and regardless of their exit code.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] With the `&&` separator, a command must succeed, i.e. yield the exit code 0, for the subsequent command to execute.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] In the following example, `CommandB` only executes if `CommandA` completes successfully, and `CommandC` only executes if `CommandB` also completes successfully.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] With the `||` separator, a command must fail, i.e. yield an exit code not equal 0, for the subsequent command to execute.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] In the following example, `CommandB` executes if `CommandA` fails, and `CommandC` executes if `CommandB` succeeds.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] The shell limits the length of a command line which includes entered text, individual environment variables that are inherited by other processes, and all environment variable expansions On Windows XP and later, the maximum length is 8191 (213-1) characters.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] On earlier versions, such as Windows 2000 or Windows NT 4.0, the maximum length is 2047 (211-1) characters.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] The shell reserves the following characters as special: &<>[]{}^=;!'+,`~ and whitespace.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] In some cases, an argument that contains such characters must be enclosed in double quotes to escape from the special character handling.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] The following sections list internal commands for implementations of the shell on various operating systems.
[src:batch-cmd/cmd-exe] The net command is available as an external command.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] IBM licensed and released it in 1981 as PC DOS 1.0 for use in its IBM Personal Computer.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Although MS-DOS and PC DOS were initially developed in parallel by Microsoft and IBM, the two products diverged after twelve years, in 1993, with recognizable differences in compatibility, syntax and capabilities.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Beginning in 1988 with DR-DOS, several competing products were released for the x86 platform.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Initially, MS-DOS was targeted at Intel 8086 processors running on computer hardware using floppy disks to store and access not only the operating system, but application software and user data as well.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Progressive version releases delivered support for other mass storage media in ever greater sizes and formats, along with added feature support for newer processors and rapidly evolving computer architectures.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Ultimately, it was the key product in Microsoft's development from a programming language company to a diverse software development firm, providing the company with essential revenue and marketing resources.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] It was also the underlying basic operating system on which early versions of Windows ran as a GUI.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] MS-DOS went through eight versions, until development ceased in 2000; version 6.22 from 1994 was the final standalone version, with versions 7 and 8 serving mostly in the background for loading Windows 9x.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The command interpreter, COMMAND.COM, runs when no application program is running.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] When an application exits, the interpreter resumes – loaded back into memory by the DOS if it was purged by the application.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] A command is processed by matching input text with either a built-in command or an executable file located on the current drive and along the command path.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Although command and file name matching is case-insensitive, the interpreter preserves the case of parameters as input.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] A command with significant program size or used infrequently tended to be a separate file in order to limit the size of the command processor program.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] MS-DOS was a renamed form of 86-DOS – owned by Seattle Computer Products, written by Tim Paterson.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] This first version was shipped in August 1980.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft, which needed an operating system for the IBM Personal Computer, hired Tim Paterson in May 1981 and bought 86-DOS 1.10 for US$25,000 that July.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft kept the version number, but renamed it MS-DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] They also licensed MS-DOS 1.10/1.14 to IBM, which, in August 1981, offered it as PC DOS 1.0 as one of three operating systems for the IBM 5150 or the IBM PC.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Within a year, Microsoft licensed MS-DOS to over 70 other companies.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] It was designed to be an OS that could run on any 8086-family computer.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Each computer would have its own distinct hardware and its own version of MS-DOS, similar to the situation that existed for CP/M, and with MS-DOS emulating the same solution as CP/M to adapt for different hardware platforms.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] To this end, MS-DOS was designed with a modular structure with internal device drivers (the DOS BIOS), minimally for primary disk drives and the console, integrated with the kernel and loaded by the boot loader, and installable device drivers for other devices loaded and integrated at boot time.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The OEM would use a development kit provided by Microsoft to build a version of MS-DOS with their basic I/O drivers and a standard Microsoft kernel, which they would typically supply on disk to end users along with the hardware.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Thus, there were many different versions of "MS-DOS" for different hardware, and there is a major distinction between an IBM-compatible (or ISA) machine and an MS-DOS [compatible] machine.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Some machines, like the Tandy 2000, were MS-DOS compatible but not IBM-compatible, so they could run software written exclusively for MS-DOS without dependence on the peripheral hardware of the IBM PC architecture.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] This design would have worked well for compatibility, if application programs had used only MS-DOS services to perform device I/O.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Indeed, the same design philosophy is embodied in Windows NT (see Hardware Abstraction Layer).
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] However, in MS-DOS's early days, the greater speed attainable by programs through direct control of hardware was of particular importance, especially for games, which often pushed the limits of their contemporary hardware.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Very soon an IBM-compatible architecture became the goal, and before long all 8086-family computers closely emulated IBM's hardware, and only a single version of MS-DOS for a fixed hardware platform was needed for the market.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft omitted multi-user support from MS-DOS because Microsoft's Unix-based operating system, Xenix, was fully multi-user.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft advertised MS-DOS and Xenix together, listing the shared features of its "single-user OS" and "the multi-user, multi-tasking, UNIX-derived operating system", and promising easy porting between them.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] After the breakup of the Bell System, however, AT&T Computer Systems started selling UNIX System V.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Believing that it could not compete with AT&T in the Unix market, Microsoft abandoned Xenix, and in 1987 transferred ownership of Xenix to the Santa Cruz Operation (SCO).
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft would later re-license the partial sources and sourceless binaries under the MIT License on September 28, 2018, making these versions partially open source.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft later released partial source code and sourceless binaries for MS-DOS 4.00 on April 25, 2024, under the same license.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] As an April Fool's Day joke in 2015, Microsoft Mobile launched a Windows Phone application called *MS-DOS Mobile* which was presented as a new mobile operating system and worked similar to MS-DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft licensed or released versions of MS-DOS under different names like Lifeboat Associates "Software Bus 86" a.k.a.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] SB-DOS, COMPAQ-DOS, NCR-DOS or Z-DOS before it eventually enforced the MS-DOS name for all versions but the IBM one, which was originally called "IBM Personal Computer DOS", later shortened to IBM PC DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] In the former Eastern bloc, MS-DOS derivatives named DCP (Disk Control Program) 3.20 and 3.30 (DCP 1700, DCP 3.3) and WDOS existed in the late 1980s.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] They were produced by the East German electronics manufacturer VEB Robotron.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] MS-DOS 2.x became popular because of reliability and use of less memory than version 3.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft DOS was released through the OEM channel, until Digital Research released DR-DOS 5.0 as a retail upgrade.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] With PC DOS 5.00.1, the IBM–Microsoft agreement started to end, and IBM entered the retail DOS market with IBM DOS 5.00.1, 5.02, 6.00 and PC DOS 6.1, 6.3, 7, 2000 and 7.1.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Localized versions of MS-DOS existed for different markets.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Affected issues include Japanese (DOS/V), Korean, Arabic (ADOS 3.3/5.0), Hebrew (HDOS 3.3/5.0), Russian (RDOS 4.01/5.0) as well as some other Eastern European versions of DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] On microcomputers based on the Intel 8086 and 8088 processors, including the IBM PC and clones, the initial competition to the PC DOS/MS-DOS line came from Digital Research, whose CP/M operating system had inspired MS-DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] There remains controversy as to whether 86-DOS was plagiarized from early versions of CP/M code.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Digital Research released CP/M-86 a few months after MS-DOS, and it was offered as an alternative to MS-DOS and Microsoft's licensing requirements, but at a higher price.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Executable programs for CP/M-86 and MS-DOS were not interchangeable with each other; many applications were sold in both MS-DOS and CP/M-86 versions until MS-DOS became preponderant (later Digital Research operating systems could run both MS-DOS and CP/M-86 software).
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] MS-DOS originally supported the simple .COM, which was modeled after a similar but binary-incompatible format known from CP/M-80.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] CP/M-86 instead supported a relocatable format using the filename extension .CMD to avoid name conflicts with CP/M-80 and MS-DOS .COM files.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] MS-DOS version 1.0 added a more advanced relocatable .EXE executable file format.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] One of the reasons for the initial success of MS-DOS over competition was the significantly lower retail price of $39.95.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Most of the machines in the early days of MS-DOS had differing system architectures and there was a certain degree of incompatibility, and subsequently vendor lock-in.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Users who began using MS-DOS with their machines were compelled to continue using the version customized for their hardware, or face trying to get all of their proprietary hardware and software to work with the new system.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] In the business world, the 808x-based machines that MS-DOS was tied to faced competition from the Unix operating system; the latter ran on many different hardware architectures.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft itself sold a version of Unix for the PC called Xenix.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] In the emerging world of home users, a variety of other computers based on various other processors were in serious competition with the IBM PC: the Apple II, Mac, Commodore 64 and others did not use the 808x processor; many 808x machines of different architectures used custom versions of MS-DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] At first all these machines were in competition.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] In time the IBM PC hardware configuration became dominant in the 808x market as software written to communicate directly with the PC hardware without using standard operating system calls ran much faster, but on true PC-compatibles only.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Most clones cost much less than IBM-branded machines of similar performance, and became widely used by home users, while IBM PCs had a large share of the business computer market.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft and IBM together began what was intended as the follow-on to MS-DOS/PC DOS, called OS/2.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] When OS/2 was released in 1987, Microsoft began an advertising campaign announcing that "DOS is Dead" and stating that version 4 was the last full release.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] OS/2 was designed for efficient multi-tasking and offered a number of advanced features that had been designed together with similar look and feel; it was seen as the legitimate heir to the "kludgy" DOS platform.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] MS-DOS had grown in spurts, with many significant features being taken or duplicated from Microsoft's other products and operating systems.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] MS-DOS also grew by incorporating, by direct licensing or feature duplicating, the functionality of tools and utilities developed by independent companies, such as Norton Utilities, PC Tools (Microsoft Anti-Virus), QEMM expanded memory manager, Stacker disk compression, and others.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] During the period when Digital Research was competing in the operating system market some computers, like the Amstrad PC1512, were sold with floppy disks for two operating systems (only one of which could be used at a time), MS-DOS and CP/M-86 or a derivative of it.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Digital Research produced DOS Plus, which was compatible with MS-DOS 2.11, supported CP/M-86 programs, had additional features including multi-tasking, and could read and write disks in CP/M and MS-DOS format.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] While OS/2 was under protracted development, Digital Research released the MS-DOS compatible DR-DOS 5.0, which included features only available as third-party add-ons for MS-DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Unwilling to lose any portion of the market, Microsoft responded by announcing the "pending" release of MS-DOS 5.0 in May 1990.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] This effectively killed most DR DOS sales until the actual release of MS-DOS 5.0 in June 1991.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Digital Research brought out DR DOS 6.0, which sold well until the "pre-announcement" of MS-DOS 6.0 again stifled the sales of DR DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft had been accused of carefully orchestrating leaks about future versions of MS-DOS in an attempt to create what in the industry is called FUD (fear, uncertainty, and doubt) regarding DR DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] For example, in October 1990, shortly after the release of DR DOS 5.0, and long before the eventual June 1991 release of MS-DOS 5.0, stories on feature enhancements in MS-DOS started to appear in *InfoWorld* and *PC Week*.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The pact between Microsoft and IBM to promote OS/2 began to fall apart in 1990 when Windows 3.0 became a marketplace success.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Many of Microsoft's further contributions to OS/2 also went into creating a third GUI replacement for DOS, Windows NT.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] IBM, which had already been developing the next version of OS/2, carried on development of the platform without Microsoft and sold it as the alternative to DOS and Windows.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] As a response to Digital Research's DR DOS 6.0, which bundled SuperStor disk compression, Microsoft opened negotiations with Stac Electronics, vendor of the most popular DOS disk compression tool, Stacker.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] In the due diligence process, Stac engineers had shown Microsoft part of the Stacker source code.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Stac was unwilling to meet Microsoft's terms for licensing Stacker and withdrew from the negotiations.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft chose to license Vertisoft's DoubleDisk, using it as the core for its DoubleSpace disk compression.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] MS-DOS 6.0 and 6.20 were released in 1993, both including the Microsoft DoubleSpace disk compression utility program.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Stac successfully sued Microsoft for patent infringement regarding the compression algorithm used in DoubleSpace.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] This resulted in the 1994 release of MS-DOS 6.21, which had disk compression removed.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Shortly afterwards came version 6.22, with a new version of the disk compression system, DriveSpace, which had a different compression algorithm to avoid the infringing code.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Prior to 1995, Microsoft licensed MS-DOS (and Windows) to computer manufacturers under three types of agreement: per-processor (a fee for each system the company sold), per-system (a fee for each system of a particular model), or per-copy (a fee for each copy of MS-DOS installed).
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The largest manufacturers used the per-processor arrangement, which had the lowest fee.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] This arrangement made it expensive for the large manufacturers to migrate to any other operating system, such as DR DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] In 1991, the U.S. government Federal Trade Commission began investigating Microsoft's licensing procedures, resulting in a 1994 settlement agreement limiting Microsoft to per-copy licensing.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Digital Research did not gain by this settlement, and years later its successor in interest, Caldera, sued Microsoft for damages in the *Caldera v.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] It was believed that the settlement ran in the order of $150 million, but was revealed in November 2009 with the release of the Settlement Agreement to be $280 million.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft also used a variety of tactics in MS-DOS and several of their applications and development tools that, while operating perfectly when running on genuine MS-DOS (and PC DOS), would break when run on another vendor's implementation of DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] All versions of Microsoft Windows have had an MS-DOS or MS-DOS-like command-line interface called MS-DOS Prompt which redirected input to MS-DOS and output from MS-DOS to the MS-DOS Prompt, or, in later versions, Command Prompt.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] This could run many DOS and variously Win32, OS/2 1.x and POSIX command-line utilities in the same command-line session, allowing piping between commands.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The user interface, and the icon up to Windows 2000, followed the native MS-DOS interface.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The Command Prompt introduced with Windows NT is not actually MS-DOS, but shares some commands with MS-DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The first versions of Windows up to 2.0 ran as a graphical user interface (GUI) on top of MS-DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Windows 3.0 and 3.1 virtualized MS-DOS in Virtual 8086 machines and used it to access the filesystem when virtualized.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The command line accessed the DOS command line (usually `COMMAND.COM`) through a Windows module (WINOLDAP.MOD).
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Windows NT-based operating systems boot to a kernel whose purpose is to load Windows and run the system.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] One cannot run Win32 applications in the loader system in the manner that OS/2, UNIX or consumer versions of Windows can launch character-mode sessions.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The command session permits running various supported command-line utilities from Win32, MS-DOS, OS/2 1.x and POSIX.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The emulators for MS-DOS, OS/2 and POSIX use the host's window in the same way that Win16 applications use the Win32 explorer.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Using the host's window allows one to pipe output between emulations.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The MS-DOS emulation takes place through the NTVDM (NT Virtual DOS Machine).
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] This is a modified SoftPC (a former product similar to VirtualPC), running a modified MS-DOS 5 (NTIO.SYS and NTDOS.SYS).
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The output is handled by the console DLLs, so that the program at the prompt (`CMD.EXE`, `4NT.EXE`, `TCC.EXE`), can see the output.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] 64-bit Windows has neither the DOS emulation, nor the DOS commands EDIT, DEBUG and EDLIN that come with 32-bit Windows.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The DOS version returns 5.00 or 5.50, depending on which API function is used to determine it.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Utilities from MS-DOS 5.00 run in this emulation without modification.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The very early beta programs of NT show MS-DOS 30.00, but programs running in MS-DOS 30.00 would assume that OS/2 was in control.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The OS/2 emulation is handled through OS2SS.EXE and OS2.EXE, and DOSCALLS.DLL.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] OS2.EXE is a version of the OS/2 shell (CMD.EXE), which passes commands down to the OS2SS.EXE, and input-output to the Windows NT shell.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Windows 2000 was the last version of NT to support OS/2.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] POSIX is emulated through the POSIX shell, but no emulated shell; the commands are handled directly in CMD.EXE.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The Command Prompt is often called the MS-DOS Prompt.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] In part, this was the official name for it in Windows 9x and early versions of Windows NT (NT 3.5 and earlier), and in part because the SoftPC emulation of DOS redirects output into it.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Actually only `COMMAND.COM` and other 16-bit commands run in an NTVDM with `AUTOEXEC.NT` and `CONFIG.NT` initialization determined by `_DEFAULT.PIF`, optionally permitting the use of Win32 console applications and internal commands with an `NTCMDPROMPT` directive.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Win32 console applications use `CMD.EXE` as their command prompt shell.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] This confusion does not exist under OS/2 because there are separate DOS and OS/2 prompts, and running a DOS program under OS/2 will launch a separate DOS window to run the application.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] All versions of Windows for Itanium (no longer sold by Microsoft) and x86-64 architectures no longer include the NTVDM and can therefore no longer natively run DOS or 16-bit Windows applications.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] There are alternatives such as virtual machine emulators such as Microsoft's own Virtual PC, as well as VMware, DOSBox etc., unofficial compatibility layers such as NTVDMx64, OTVDM (WineVDM), Win3mu and others.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The introduction of Windows 3.0 in 1990, with an easy-to-use graphical user interface, marked the beginning of the end for the command-line driven MS-DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] With the release of Windows 95 (and continuing in the Windows 9x product line through to Windows Me), an integrated version of MS-DOS was used for bootstrapping, troubleshooting, and backwards-compatibility with old DOS software, particularly games, and no longer released as a standalone product.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] In Windows 95, the DOS, called MS-DOS 7, can be booted separately, without the Windows GUI; this capability was retained through Windows 98 Second Edition.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Windows Me removed the capability to boot its underlying MS-DOS 8.0 alone from a hard disk, but retained the ability to make a DOS boot floppy disk (called an "Emergency Boot Disk") and can be hacked to restore full access to the underlying DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] On December 31, 2001, Microsoft declared all versions of MS-DOS (6.22 and older) obsolete and stopped providing support and updates for the system.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] As MS-DOS 7.0 was a part of Windows 95, support for it also ended when Windows 95 extended support ended on December 31, 2001.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] As MS-DOS 7.10 and MS-DOS 8.0 were part of Windows 98 and Windows ME, respectively, support ended when Windows 98 and ME extended support ended on July 11, 2006, thus ending support and updates of MS-DOS from Microsoft.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] 64-bit versions of Windows NT prior to Windows 11 (and Windows Server 2008 R2 by extension) do not provide DOS emulation and cannot run DOS applications natively.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Windows XP onwards contains a copy of the Windows Me boot disk, stripped down to bootstrap only.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] This is accessible only by formatting a floppy as an "MS-DOS startup disk".
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Files like the driver for the CD-ROM support were deleted from the Windows Me bootdisk and the startup files (AUTOEXEC.BAT and CONFIG.SYS) no longer had content.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] This modified disk was the base for creating the MS-DOS image for Windows XP.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Some of the deleted files can be recovered with an undelete tool.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The creation of the MS-DOS startup disk was then carried over to later versions of Windows, with the majority of its contents remaining unchanged from its introduction in Windows XP.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] When creating a DOS startup disk on Windows Vista, the files on the startup disk are dated April 18, 2005, but are otherwise unchanged from XP, including the string "MS-DOS Version 8 Copyright 1981–1999 Microsoft Corp" inside `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Windows 7, 8, and 8.1 can also create a MS-DOS startup disk, which are otherwise unchanged from XP and Vista.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Starting with Windows 10, the ability to create a MS-DOS startup disk has been removed, and so either a virtual machine running MS-DOS or an older version (in a virtual machine or dual boot) must be used to format a floppy disk, or an image must be obtained from an external source.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Other solutions include using DOS compatible alternatives, such as FreeDOS or even copying the required files and boot sector themselves.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The last remaining components related to MS-DOS was the NTVDM component, which was removed entirely in Windows starting with Windows 11 as the operating system dropped support for 32-bit processors in favor of being solely offered in 64-bit versions only.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] This effectively ended any association of MS-DOS within Microsoft Windows after 36 years.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] MS-DOS 6.22 was the last standalone version produced by Microsoft for Intel 8088, Intel 8086, and Intel 80286 processors, which remains available for download via their MSDN, volume license, and OEM license partner websites, for customers with valid login credentials.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] MS-DOS is still used in embedded x86 systems due to its simple architecture and minimal memory and processor requirements, though some current products have switched to the still-maintained open-source alternative FreeDOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] In 2018, Microsoft released the source code for MS-DOS 1.25 and 2.0 on GitHub under the open source MIT License, and in 2024 released the source code for MS-DOS 4.00 in the same repository.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The purpose of this, according to Microsoft, is mainly for education and experimentation with historic operating systems and for new programmers to gain an understanding of how low-level software works, both historic and current.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] According to program manager Rich Turner, the other versions could not be open-sourced due to third-party licensing restrictions.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Due to the historical nature of the software, Microsoft will not accept any pull requests to the code.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] However, its permissive MIT License allows users to download, modify and fork the software as long as credit is given to its original authors.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] From 1983 onwards, various companies worked on graphical user interfaces (GUIs) capable of running on PC hardware.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] However, this required duplicated effort and did not provide much consistency in interface design (even between products from the same company).
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Later, in 1985, Microsoft Windows 1.0 was released as Microsoft's first attempt at providing a consistent user interface (for applications).
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] The early versions of Windows ran on top of MS-DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] At first Windows met with little success, but this was also true for most other companies' efforts as well, for example GEM.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] After version 3.0, Windows gained market acceptance.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Windows 9x used MS-DOS to boot the Windows kernel in protected mode.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Basic features related to the file system, such as long file names, were only available to DOS applications when running through Windows.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Windows NT runs independently of DOS but includes NTVDM, a component for simulating a DOS environment for legacy applications.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] It was not included with Windows 11 as the operating system is exclusively offered in 64-bit architectures such as x86-64.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] It and MS-DOS were identical products that eventually diverged starting with MS-DOS version 6.0.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Digital Research did not follow Microsoft's version numbering scheme.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] For example, MS-DOS 4, released in July 1988, was followed by DR DOS 5.0 in May 1990.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] MS-DOS 5.0 came in April 1991, and DR DOS 6.0 was released the following June.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] These products are collectively referred to as "DOS", even though "Disk Operating System" is a generic term used on other systems unrelated to the x86 and IBM PC.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] "MS-DOS" can also be a generic reference to DOS on IBM PC compatible computers.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Microsoft's control of the Windows platform, and their programming practices which intentionally made Windows appear as if it ran poorly on competing versions of DOS, crippled the ability of other DOS makers to continue to compete with MS-DOS.
[src:batch-cmd/ms-dos] Digital Research had to release interim releases to circumvent Windows limitations inserted artificially, designed specifically to provide Microsoft with a competitive advantage.
[src:batch-cmd/nt] Get the security descriptor (SDDL) for an object (file, directory, reg key).
[src:batch-cmd/nt] Encrypt or Decrypt files/folders, overwrite data.
[src:batch-cmd/nt] Pause, resume, cancel, or list print jobs.
[src:batch-cmd/nt] Add, delete, or list printer connections.
[src:batch-cmd/nt] Manage Printer Ports, change port configuration.
[src:batch-cmd/nt] Set security for an object (file, directory, reg key etc).
[src:batch-cmd/nt] To scroll this page, press [ a – z ] on the keyboard, or '\' to Search.
[src:batch-cmd/nt] Commands marked • are *Internal* commands only available within the CMD shell.
[src:batch-cmd/nt] All other commands (not marked with •) are *external* commands.
[src:batch-cmd/nt] External commands may be used under the CMD shell, PowerShell, or directly from START-RUN.
